{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"239bd6ed-a5f4-478c-bc24-71de50147819","content":"When `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is set to `1` (via `<startup>` element in app config or registry), it changes how the CLR activation system binds legacy COM components and mixed-mode assemblies:\n\n**What it does:**\n- Forces CLR v2 (`.NET 2.0/3.5`) components to load into the **v4 runtime** instead of requesting their own v2 runtime.\n- Mirrors the \"old\" .NET 2.0 behavior where the process runtime handled everything, regardless of the component's built-in version.\n\n**Practical effects:**\n1. **Mixed-mode C++/CLI DLLs** built against CLR v2 will activate in the v4 runtime without errors.\n2. **Legacy COM components** targeting v2 bind to v4 rather than trying (and potentially failing) to load a side-by-side v2 CLR.\n3. Avoids the v4-era default behavior of loading multiple runtimes side-by-side for different version requests.\n\n**When you'd see this:** Typically in apps that host or load older plugins/assemblies and need them to \"just work\" under .NET 4.x without recompiling.\n\n**Risks:** Components designed for CLR v2 may encounter subtle behavior changes under v4 (e.g., security model, exception handling). It effectively opts out of true side-by-side CLR hosting.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"076c1835-fa36-49b6-ba0a-ca5a254ab552","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation logging, specifically about the `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` setting. This is a .NET Framework question about runtime activation behavior. Let me answer from my knowledge since this is a well-known .NET concept.","outputTokens":412},"id":"e36106af-9d7c-4f65-b310-f564f8a8452c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:16:56.265Z","parentId":"a577409c-ffcf-49b6-93e3-f4510c5d9588"}
